00:39:32.710 --> 00:39:34.400
RUDY RUCKER: Hi.

00:39:34.400 --> 00:39:37.100
I recently was reading a
novel by Charles Stross,

00:39:37.100 --> 00:39:39.800
he's one of my favorite
science fiction writers,

00:39:39.800 --> 00:39:42.560
and he was talking
about a guy who

00:39:42.560 --> 00:39:44.950
says he has Impostor Syndrome.

00:39:44.950 --> 00:39:47.430
And I'd never heard that phrase
before, and I looked it up.

00:39:47.430 --> 00:39:51.110
And it's something that
some well-known people have.

00:39:51.110 --> 00:39:52.800
They feel like they're faking.

00:39:52.800 --> 00:39:56.220
So I taught software engineering
at San Jose State for 20 years

00:39:56.220 --> 00:39:58.550
and I don't know anything
about programming.

00:39:58.550 --> 00:40:00.260
I was faking.

00:40:00.260 --> 00:40:03.150
And I've published 20 novels,
and I don't know how to write.

00:40:03.150 --> 00:40:04.740
I've been faking.

00:40:04.740 --> 00:40:08.680
And I'm in the
Hieroglyph anthology,

00:40:08.680 --> 00:40:10.450
and I'm faking
because I'm not making

00:40:10.450 --> 00:40:13.365
any constructive suggestions
about the future.

00:40:17.970 --> 00:40:20.720
I thought I would come
up with one specific idea

00:40:20.720 --> 00:40:22.780
that, actually,
you could implement

00:40:22.780 --> 00:40:24.330
using Google's technology.

00:40:24.330 --> 00:40:25.900
It would be pretty easy.

00:40:25.900 --> 00:40:28.380
It's something I
call the lifebox.

00:40:28.380 --> 00:40:30.480
And this is an idea
I've been talking

00:40:30.480 --> 00:40:32.870
about for 20 or 30 years.

00:40:32.870 --> 00:40:35.670
Recently some people have
tried to commercialize it.

00:40:35.670 --> 00:40:38.090
And the idea is fairly simple.

00:40:38.090 --> 00:40:42.990
You'd like to have something
like a website that

00:40:42.990 --> 00:40:45.710
would simulate you,
sort of like something

00:40:45.710 --> 00:40:47.190
that passes the Turing Test.

00:40:47.190 --> 00:40:50.660
So if somebody wanted to talk
to me, they'd go to this site

00:40:50.660 --> 00:40:54.770
and they would ask questions and
the program would answer them.

00:40:54.770 --> 00:40:59.500
And it would basically feel
as if they were talking to me.

00:40:59.500 --> 00:41:03.340
And I realize there's a
pretty easy way to fake it.

00:41:03.340 --> 00:41:06.270
I have a page called
"Rudy's Lifebox."

00:41:06.270 --> 00:41:08.800
If you root around on my
blog, you can find it:

00:41:08.800 --> 00:41:11.340
rudyrucker.com/blog.

00:41:11.340 --> 00:41:14.300
And then there's
Rudy's hyphen lifebox.

00:41:14.300 --> 00:41:17.350
And you can restrict
Google Search so it only

00:41:17.350 --> 00:41:23.375
searches one website, so it
just searches all the files

00:41:23.375 --> 00:41:24.500
that are on rudyrucker.com.

00:41:24.500 --> 00:41:28.220
And I have a lot
of things up there.

00:41:28.220 --> 00:41:31.230
I posted a lot of
books, a lot of notes.

00:41:31.230 --> 00:41:34.920
And one thing I found with the
links that you get from that,

00:41:34.920 --> 00:41:37.790
if you put up a PDF,
it isn't really good,

00:41:37.790 --> 00:41:42.300
because-- I don't know why
it is, something about Google

00:41:42.300 --> 00:41:46.480
versus Adobe or something-- when
they return you a link to a PDF

00:41:46.480 --> 00:41:48.760
document, it's just a
link to the document

00:41:48.760 --> 00:41:51.730
and it's not a link down into
the site in the document.

00:41:51.730 --> 00:41:52.850
So it's slow.

00:41:52.850 --> 00:41:55.690
It's not a good interface.

00:41:55.690 --> 00:41:57.510
So because of that
I've been going

00:41:57.510 --> 00:42:00.890
to the trouble of posting
things like-- whenever I write

00:42:00.890 --> 00:42:03.729
a novel, I post a
book-length bunch

00:42:03.729 --> 00:42:05.270
of notes about how
I wrote the novel.

00:42:05.270 --> 00:42:07.960
While I'm writing a
novel, I write the notes

00:42:07.960 --> 00:42:10.420
so then when I don't want to
write, I can write the notes.

00:42:10.420 --> 00:42:12.480
And then when I'm done,
I put the notes up,

00:42:12.480 --> 00:42:15.630
and nowadays I put them
up as big web pages

00:42:15.630 --> 00:42:18.850
so that you can
search into them.

00:42:18.850 --> 00:42:21.840
And so that's-- really,
you don't need the AI.

00:42:21.840 --> 00:42:24.350
You can fake AI if
you have enough data.

00:42:24.350 --> 00:42:26.530
That's the whole thing.

00:42:26.530 --> 00:42:31.880
If you have maybe 10,000
pages that somebody's written,

00:42:31.880 --> 00:42:35.380
you can always find the
right thing in there.

00:42:35.380 --> 00:42:38.000
I think they tried doing this
with the fake Phil Dick head

00:42:38.000 --> 00:42:40.630
that they made, that they
lost on the airplane.

00:42:40.630 --> 00:42:43.170
And they had-- it would
search through his works

00:42:43.170 --> 00:42:45.330
and find phrases.

00:42:45.330 --> 00:42:47.920
And I think this could
work pretty well.

00:42:47.920 --> 00:42:48.930
It'd be a good product.

00:42:48.930 --> 00:42:51.000
People would like it.

00:42:51.000 --> 00:42:53.430
And there are some
sleazebags trying

00:42:53.430 --> 00:42:55.732
to monetize this product.

00:42:55.732 --> 00:42:57.190
I call them sleazebags
because they

00:42:57.190 --> 00:43:00.850
don't mention that I
had the idea first.

00:43:00.850 --> 00:43:04.280
But I don't care enough about
it to try to monetize it,

00:43:04.280 --> 00:43:07.790
so I'm giving you this.

00:43:07.790 --> 00:43:10.662
OK, so that's all I
have for right now.

00:43:10.662 --> 00:43:12.470
KATHRYN CRAMER: Annalee?

00:43:12.470 --> 00:43:15.970
ANNALEE NEWITZ: OK, so, I
have some biotechnology here,

00:43:15.970 --> 00:43:16.540
by the way.

00:43:16.540 --> 00:43:18.880
This is not actually
not technology.

00:43:18.880 --> 00:43:21.260
I just want to note
that about paper.

00:43:21.260 --> 00:43:24.540
So my idea for the
book, for Hieroglyph,

00:43:24.540 --> 00:43:26.850
came out of the book that
I published last year,

00:43:26.850 --> 00:43:29.430
"Scatter, Adapt, and Remember,"
which is pretty optimistic

00:43:29.430 --> 00:43:32.060
because I talk about humans
surviving a mass extinction,

00:43:32.060 --> 00:43:35.650
which people seemed to think
was radically optimistic

00:43:35.650 --> 00:43:37.320
that we would make it through.

00:43:37.320 --> 00:43:40.935
And one of the solutions
that I proposed,

00:43:40.935 --> 00:43:42.994
and that lots of the
scientists and engineers I

00:43:42.994 --> 00:43:44.410
talked to proposed,
was that we'll

00:43:44.410 --> 00:43:46.950
survive by creating
more sustainable cities.

00:43:46.950 --> 00:43:50.020
Bigger, more high-tech,
but more sustainable.

00:43:50.020 --> 00:43:52.306
So the interesting
thing about thinking

00:43:52.306 --> 00:43:54.430
about these future cities
that would be sustainable

00:43:54.430 --> 00:43:57.250
is that, I think when
most of us imagine

00:43:57.250 --> 00:44:00.270
awesome cities of the
future, we picture something

00:44:00.270 --> 00:44:04.830
like a city that's like an
Apple watch or something

00:44:04.830 --> 00:44:05.700
out of Tron Legacy.

00:44:05.700 --> 00:44:06.200
Right?

00:44:06.200 --> 00:44:10.440
Like curves, and shiny
and clean and chrome.

00:44:10.440 --> 00:44:13.380
Something with soaring towers.

00:44:13.380 --> 00:44:15.570
I actually think
that's possible.

00:44:15.570 --> 00:44:18.720
But it's also possible that
a city of the future that

00:44:18.720 --> 00:44:22.610
was sustainable would look
like a very ancient city.

00:44:22.610 --> 00:44:24.930
So let me give you an example.

00:44:24.930 --> 00:44:27.091
Let's talk about St.
Louis, because St. Louis

00:44:27.091 --> 00:44:28.590
is interesting for
a lot of reasons.

00:44:28.590 --> 00:44:31.320
For one, its
industries are highly

00:44:31.320 --> 00:44:32.590
dependent on fossil fuel.

00:44:32.590 --> 00:44:35.940
It's a coal-based economy there.

00:44:35.940 --> 00:44:39.300
And also, St. Louis is
located right across the river

00:44:39.300 --> 00:44:40.940
from an ancient city.

00:44:40.940 --> 00:44:43.290
It's about 1,000 years old.

00:44:43.290 --> 00:44:46.020
It had about 30,000
people that live there

00:44:46.020 --> 00:44:48.100
for several hundred years.

00:44:48.100 --> 00:44:50.470
And what dominated the
horizon of the city-- which

00:44:50.470 --> 00:44:52.440
is called Cahokia now,
and you can actually

00:44:52.440 --> 00:44:54.620
see some of the
remains of that city

00:44:54.620 --> 00:44:58.310
that weren't knocked down for
the freeway-- the city was

00:44:58.310 --> 00:45:01.300
dominated by these
huge earthen pyramids.

00:45:01.300 --> 00:45:02.230
Enormous!

00:45:02.230 --> 00:45:04.330
Basically like the
pyramids in Egypt,

00:45:04.330 --> 00:45:07.540
but made from hard-packed earth.

00:45:07.540 --> 00:45:10.350
And so it's my
proposal that we think

00:45:10.350 --> 00:45:13.607
about that as a kind
of a model for how

00:45:13.607 --> 00:45:14.940
a city might look in the future.

00:45:14.940 --> 00:45:17.350
And I have one
magic word for you

00:45:17.350 --> 00:45:19.320
about how it's all
going to happen.

00:45:19.320 --> 00:45:23.540
And that word is
"cyanobacteria."

00:45:23.540 --> 00:45:26.347
So if you're a scientist,
you might call a cyano

00:45:26.347 --> 00:45:27.430
if you're working with it.

00:45:27.430 --> 00:45:29.850
You might know it
as blue-green algae,

00:45:29.850 --> 00:45:32.020
and you've seen it
all over the place.

00:45:32.020 --> 00:45:35.200
It's a model organism that's
used a lot in synthetic biology

00:45:35.200 --> 00:45:38.260
because we understand a lot
of the metabolic pathways.

00:45:38.260 --> 00:45:41.530
We understand a lot of the
genetic pathways that run it.

00:45:41.530 --> 00:45:44.390
And there's actually a
lab in St. Louis, run

00:45:44.390 --> 00:45:47.980
by a guy named Himadi
Pakrasi, that's figured out

00:45:47.980 --> 00:45:52.170
a way to tweak the genome
of a certain strain of cyano

00:45:52.170 --> 00:45:56.470
to produce a lot more
hydrogen than it had been.

00:45:56.470 --> 00:45:59.910
And this could be used,
putatively, for hydrogen fuel.

00:45:59.910 --> 00:46:03.920
And so I think that a future
that's-- I think that we could

00:46:03.920 --> 00:46:07.070
start thinking about a future
where instead of investing

00:46:07.070 --> 00:46:09.990
in new ways to suck fossil
fuels out of the planet,

00:46:09.990 --> 00:46:13.250
we start thinking about ways
we could use synthetic biology

00:46:13.250 --> 00:46:17.400
to alter microorganisms
to produce fuel.

00:46:17.400 --> 00:46:21.749
And I think that might be--
that killer app, killer

00:46:21.749 --> 00:46:24.040
biological app-- might be
the way we'd kind of get over

00:46:24.040 --> 00:46:28.180
the hump in terms of
bringing synthetic biology

00:46:28.180 --> 00:46:30.020
into our cities as
something that we could

00:46:30.020 --> 00:46:33.130
use not just for making
fuel, which is awesome,

00:46:33.130 --> 00:46:35.340
but also for building with.

00:46:35.340 --> 00:46:39.140
So instead of living
in houses and buildings

00:46:39.140 --> 00:46:42.440
that are made of dead
materials like dead trees;

00:46:42.440 --> 00:46:44.502
if you're building
anything with calcium,

00:46:44.502 --> 00:46:45.960
calcium carbonate
in it, of course,

00:46:45.960 --> 00:46:48.020
you're building
with dead bodies.

00:46:48.020 --> 00:46:51.321
And so these are
dead structures.

00:46:51.321 --> 00:46:53.570
But what if we were building
out of living structures?

00:46:53.570 --> 00:46:58.250
What if we altered plants to
do things like filter our air?

00:46:58.250 --> 00:46:59.910
Filter our water?

00:46:59.910 --> 00:47:04.270
What if we grew cyano not
just for energy production,

00:47:04.270 --> 00:47:07.354
but to produce other kinds
of chemicals as well.

00:47:07.354 --> 00:47:09.770
And of course there's all kinds
of labs around the country

00:47:09.770 --> 00:47:12.005
right now where this
stuff is going on.

00:47:12.005 --> 00:47:16.410
Where we're altering things like
yeast and other microorganisms

00:47:16.410 --> 00:47:17.850
to produce chemicals
that now are

00:47:17.850 --> 00:47:21.160
produced through messy
industrial processes.

00:47:21.160 --> 00:47:24.530
So the synthetic biology city.

00:47:24.530 --> 00:47:27.049
Let's just imagine
for minute that mound

00:47:27.049 --> 00:47:28.090
that I was talking about.

00:47:28.090 --> 00:47:31.170
So you're going into St. Louis.

00:47:31.170 --> 00:47:34.130
You're going to work at Google
St. Louis let's pretend that

00:47:34.130 --> 00:47:34.630
exists.

00:47:34.630 --> 00:47:35.609
Does that exist?

00:47:35.609 --> 00:47:36.150
I don't know.

00:47:36.150 --> 00:47:40.160
Anyway, so, you see
this huge mound,

00:47:40.160 --> 00:47:41.990
which is basically
the equivalent

00:47:41.990 --> 00:47:43.910
of a skyscraper in the city.

00:47:43.910 --> 00:47:47.200
So first of all, because it's
this mound and you've got,

00:47:47.200 --> 00:47:52.140
say, shops in it, you have
offices, you have living areas.

00:47:52.140 --> 00:47:54.230
So it's already well
insulated, right?

00:47:54.230 --> 00:47:56.320
Because you've got the
perfect earthen mound,

00:47:56.320 --> 00:47:58.990
so it's going to be cool
in the summer and warmer

00:47:58.990 --> 00:48:00.190
in the winter.

00:48:00.190 --> 00:48:03.540
It's shot through with
all kinds of tunnels

00:48:03.540 --> 00:48:06.230
that are for bringing in fresh
air, which of course is being

00:48:06.230 --> 00:48:08.540
filtered by microorganisms.

00:48:08.540 --> 00:48:11.840
You've got ways of bringing
water into the structure

00:48:11.840 --> 00:48:15.197
so that you don't have this
problem where you're keeping

00:48:15.197 --> 00:48:17.030
water out of the structure
and therefore you

00:48:17.030 --> 00:48:18.660
get all this water
runoff, which is

00:48:18.660 --> 00:48:20.870
one of our big problems
with ocean acidification,

00:48:20.870 --> 00:48:22.630
among other things.

00:48:22.630 --> 00:48:25.210
And this mound is
covered in plants.

00:48:25.210 --> 00:48:27.640
All these biologically
altered plants

00:48:27.640 --> 00:48:31.110
that might be part of the
building's filtration systems

00:48:31.110 --> 00:48:33.470
and part of its metabolism.

00:48:33.470 --> 00:48:35.420
And so part of what
we're thinking about here

00:48:35.420 --> 00:48:39.420
is: What would a city be
like if it functioned exactly

00:48:39.420 --> 00:48:43.050
like, or very similar to,
the ecosystem around the city

00:48:43.050 --> 00:48:43.550
itself?

00:48:43.550 --> 00:48:47.750
The city is becoming
its own ecosystem.

00:48:47.750 --> 00:48:49.500
A genetically
modified ecosystem,

00:48:49.500 --> 00:48:51.570
but one that's
diverse and in balance

00:48:51.570 --> 00:48:53.720
with the life around it.

00:48:53.720 --> 00:48:57.250
So say you're coming into work
and you see this building.

00:48:57.250 --> 00:49:00.930
One of the other things
you might see on this mound

00:49:00.930 --> 00:49:02.307
is that it's not smooth.

00:49:02.307 --> 00:49:04.390
I mean, we've already said
it's covered in plants,

00:49:04.390 --> 00:49:07.300
it's covered in some grasses
that help with water runoff.

00:49:07.300 --> 00:49:11.520
But it's also covered in a
lot of pock marks and scars.

00:49:11.520 --> 00:49:15.380
This doesn't look like the
shiny Tron Legacy future

00:49:15.380 --> 00:49:16.369
that you might imagine.

00:49:16.369 --> 00:49:17.910
And the reason why
it looks like that

00:49:17.910 --> 00:49:20.520
is because this is
a structure that's

00:49:20.520 --> 00:49:24.710
being repaired constantly,
using bacteria.

00:49:24.710 --> 00:49:26.680
So say it develops
a crack, or there's

00:49:26.680 --> 00:49:28.480
some kind of other
structural damage.

00:49:28.480 --> 00:49:32.130
You might use a form of
bacteria to repair that crack.

00:49:32.130 --> 00:49:34.370
The bacteria would
go in, replicate,

00:49:34.370 --> 00:49:39.130
extrude some kind of glue,
and harden into concrete.

00:49:39.130 --> 00:49:41.870
And if you sat down at your
computer in this building,

00:49:41.870 --> 00:49:44.600
which would probably be made
with virus shells-- modified

00:49:44.600 --> 00:49:47.590
viruses producing shells
that produce a computer

00:49:47.590 --> 00:49:50.920
monitor for you-- that's, by the
way, being done in a lab right

00:49:50.920 --> 00:49:57.040
now at MIT-- you might look out
the window of your nice office

00:49:57.040 --> 00:49:59.900
in this mound, and see
something really extraordinary.

00:49:59.900 --> 00:50:02.700
Somebody in that future, in
this synthetic biology future,

00:50:02.700 --> 00:50:04.830
will have taken
Stewart Brand's advice

00:50:04.830 --> 00:50:06.870
and de-extincted mastodons.

00:50:06.870 --> 00:50:10.900
To bring them in to eat grass
and to stomp on the roads

00:50:10.900 --> 00:50:14.890
to keep the dust down,
and maybe trim the bushes.

00:50:14.890 --> 00:50:17.420
And all of that,
this future where

00:50:17.420 --> 00:50:19.570
you have a sustainable
building that functions

00:50:19.570 --> 00:50:25.000
like an ecosystem, and mastodons
outside, will come from a world

00:50:25.000 --> 00:50:27.950
where a simple tweak
to cyanobacteria

00:50:27.950 --> 00:50:31.210
might usher in a future
shaped by synthetic biology.

00:50:31.210 --> 00:50:32.437
Thanks.

00:50:32.437 --> 00:50:34.020
AUDIENCE: So this
is great, and thanks

00:50:34.020 --> 00:50:36.370
for doing this and coming here.

00:50:36.370 --> 00:50:39.420
Imma let you finish
and all, but I just

00:50:39.420 --> 00:50:42.980
wanted to say in
a contrary vein,

00:50:42.980 --> 00:50:46.930
as a field don't stop doing
the pessimistic stuff.

00:50:46.930 --> 00:50:50.680
Because I think as
engineers our failure mode

00:50:50.680 --> 00:50:53.760
is we're too optimistic,
and we need somebody

00:50:53.760 --> 00:50:57.731
to write the unit tests
that we have to pass.

00:50:57.731 --> 00:50:58.230
Right?

00:50:58.230 --> 00:51:01.196
So I want to know if I'm
making a program, what

00:51:01.196 --> 00:51:02.570
are all the ways
it can go wrong?

00:51:02.570 --> 00:51:04.695
I'm not good at thinking
of them, but you guys are.

00:51:04.695 --> 00:51:06.380
So keep doing that too.

00:51:06.380 --> 00:51:07.876
NEAL STEPHENSON: Thanks.

00:51:07.876 --> 00:51:10.320
Thanks, Peter.

00:51:10.320 --> 00:51:12.640
Kathryn can actually talk
to this a little bit,

00:51:12.640 --> 00:51:15.660
but I'll say that
there's more-- but when

00:51:15.660 --> 00:51:17.230
I saw the stories
they came out I

00:51:17.230 --> 00:51:20.660
was pleased by how
much bad was in them.

00:51:24.360 --> 00:51:27.160
People didn't go too far in
the optimistic direction.

00:51:27.160 --> 00:51:32.780
And indeed, my story
about the tower enlivened

00:51:32.780 --> 00:51:36.470
by a giant lightning
bolt strike from a thing

00:51:36.470 --> 00:51:40.740
called an upward super-bolt
that kills somebody.

00:51:40.740 --> 00:51:47.720
So I think the dystopian thing
has gone too deep into our DNA

00:51:47.720 --> 00:51:50.185
at this point ever to go away.

00:51:50.185 --> 00:51:51.060
KATHRYN CRAMER: Yeah.

00:51:51.060 --> 00:51:53.710
A touchstone phrase of mine
when we were editing the book

00:51:53.710 --> 00:51:56.080
is that one wouldn't want
to write in an airplane that

00:51:56.080 --> 00:51:58.460
had been designed by somebody
who had never thought

00:51:58.460 --> 00:52:00.245
of the possibility
that planes crash.

00:52:03.300 --> 00:52:04.320
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:52:04.320 --> 00:52:06.740
So I had a question.

00:52:06.740 --> 00:52:11.110
You were talking about a
very biosynthetic future.

00:52:11.110 --> 00:52:13.290
Have you heard
anything more recent

00:52:13.290 --> 00:52:16.380
about, say, cultured
meat, or anything?

00:52:16.380 --> 00:52:21.390
Does that come through any
of the stories in Hieroglyph?

00:52:21.390 --> 00:52:23.810
ANNALEE NEWITZ: I can't
speak to other stories.

00:52:23.810 --> 00:52:26.540
NEAL STEPHENSON: I don't think
we have any meat stories.

00:52:26.540 --> 00:52:27.873
ANNALEE NEWITZ: No meat stories.

00:52:27.873 --> 00:52:31.350
We also don't have an artificial
womb so, what the hell?

00:52:31.350 --> 00:52:34.520
But what I will
say is that I think

00:52:34.520 --> 00:52:38.350
any kind of utopian vision that
includes synthetic biology has

00:52:38.350 --> 00:52:42.430
to include some kind
of synthetic meat.

00:52:42.430 --> 00:52:43.990
Tissue-engineered meat.

00:52:43.990 --> 00:52:45.500
I love to think about it.

00:52:45.500 --> 00:52:47.760
In my story I do talk
about a warehouse

00:52:47.760 --> 00:52:52.320
where they're growing
sort of sheets of meat.

00:52:52.320 --> 00:52:55.270
And I think that's-- I
mean, it's not just humane,

00:52:55.270 --> 00:52:59.336
but it's also a better way to
not perturb the carbon cycle.

00:52:59.336 --> 00:53:00.710
Because, I mean,
frankly, there's

00:53:00.710 --> 00:53:02.480
less farting if you
have sheets of meat.

00:53:02.480 --> 00:53:02.980
Right?

00:53:02.980 --> 00:53:07.060
Like it's going to be a better,
more sustainable system.

00:53:07.060 --> 00:53:08.720
AUDIENCE: Yeah, no,
I definitely really

00:53:08.720 --> 00:53:10.630
like those properties of it.

00:53:10.630 --> 00:53:11.980
It's not cruel.

00:53:11.980 --> 00:53:13.850
It's not--

00:53:13.850 --> 00:53:16.066
ANNALEE NEWITZ: One
day it will be tasty.

00:53:16.066 --> 00:53:17.210
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:17.210 --> 00:53:18.710
AUDIENCE: But then
you start getting

00:53:18.710 --> 00:53:20.920
into problems where
it's a monoculture.

00:53:20.920 --> 00:53:24.410
You've got this whole
sheet, but it's all

00:53:24.410 --> 00:53:29.630
weak to the same
bacteria or virus.

00:53:29.630 --> 00:53:32.410
RUDY RUCKER: I have quite a
bit about artificial biology

00:53:32.410 --> 00:53:35.480
in my story in there,
"Quantum Telepathy."

00:53:35.480 --> 00:53:37.690
And that's something that's
always interested me.

00:53:37.690 --> 00:53:40.600
That we could eventually
get rid of all the machines

00:53:40.600 --> 00:53:41.230
that we have.

00:53:41.230 --> 00:53:44.840
I mean, it would be more natural
to have everything be alive.

00:53:44.840 --> 00:53:46.930
We used to talk about
nanotechnology a lot,

00:53:46.930 --> 00:53:50.180
and really biology
is the nanotechnology

00:53:50.180 --> 00:53:51.170
we've already got.

00:53:51.170 --> 00:53:54.860
We've really just
haven't even scratched

00:53:54.860 --> 00:53:57.510
the surface of what we can do.

00:53:57.510 --> 00:54:01.390
Speaking of cultured meat,
in my novel "Freeward,"

00:54:01.390 --> 00:54:06.180
there's a woman-- and I
think she's a senator--

00:54:06.180 --> 00:54:09.480
and she produces meat
made from her own cells.

00:54:09.480 --> 00:54:12.010
It's called "Wendy meat."

00:54:12.010 --> 00:54:14.600
She's very popular.

00:54:14.600 --> 00:54:17.887
ANNALEE NEWITZ: But I just want
to add that I think that as we

00:54:17.887 --> 00:54:20.470
think about these features we
do have to think about how do we

00:54:20.470 --> 00:54:23.790
introduce diversity
into our manufactured .

00:54:23.790 --> 00:54:27.010
Biology because diversity is
what's key to any ecosystem,

00:54:27.010 --> 00:54:30.010
so ecosystem engineering has
to include a focus on that.

00:54:30.010 --> 00:54:32.800
So that you won't have all your
meat getting the same disease,

00:54:32.800 --> 00:54:36.654
or all your cyanobacteria coming
down with some kind of rot.

00:54:36.654 --> 00:54:38.320
ED FINN: And of course
this is a problem

00:54:38.320 --> 00:54:40.460
with industrial
agriculture now, right?

00:54:40.460 --> 00:54:45.090
We have fewer and fewer species
of that plants and animals

00:54:45.090 --> 00:54:47.910
that we're relying on
to mass produce things.

00:54:47.910 --> 00:54:50.940
KATHRYN CRAMER: Actually, I
want to point your attention

00:54:50.940 --> 00:54:54.200
towards an essay that was
posted on the Hieroglyph website

00:54:54.200 --> 00:54:56.962
a couple of days ago.

00:54:56.962 --> 00:54:58.670
I don't remember
exactly the title of it,

00:54:58.670 --> 00:55:01.240
but it was the
solar punk manifesto

00:55:01.240 --> 00:55:03.620
that dealt was the some
of the issues in terms

00:55:03.620 --> 00:55:07.890
of small-scale infrastructure
as a form of resistance

00:55:07.890 --> 00:55:09.220
to large-scale infrastructure.

00:55:09.220 --> 00:55:13.030
And I think in that framework,
diversity in biology

00:55:13.030 --> 00:55:13.800
is a key issue.

00:55:16.640 --> 00:55:20.070
AUDIENCE: So I was curious about
the genesis of the project.

00:55:20.070 --> 00:55:22.730
You mentioned that there
was a conversation about us

00:55:22.730 --> 00:55:25.180
as a society not
thinking big anymore.

00:55:25.180 --> 00:55:30.912
And it made me think that I
feel like around here there

00:55:30.912 --> 00:55:32.620
are a lot of people
who are thinking big,

00:55:32.620 --> 00:55:36.390
but our society has sort of--
we've sort of tied ourselves up

00:55:36.390 --> 00:55:37.000
in knots.

00:55:37.000 --> 00:55:42.300
So, like, your super-tall
tower idea sounds amazing,

00:55:42.300 --> 00:55:46.620
but around here it's illegal
to build tall buildings.

00:55:46.620 --> 00:55:49.980
We have the anti-invention of
the high limit to deal with.

00:55:49.980 --> 00:55:54.280
So I'm curious why you think
the problem is that nobody

00:55:54.280 --> 00:55:57.470
has designed the 20-kilometer
tower yet, when we can't even

00:55:57.470 --> 00:56:01.170
build a 100-story
building around here.

00:56:01.170 --> 00:56:03.430
NEAL STEPHENSON: I actually
don't think that anymore.

00:56:03.430 --> 00:56:06.670
I actually-- since we
started this project,

00:56:06.670 --> 00:56:09.480
my thinking has been going
in the direction of, "What

00:56:09.480 --> 00:56:11.550
actually is the
scarce resource?"

00:56:11.550 --> 00:56:17.490
And my first inclination
was to believe

00:56:17.490 --> 00:56:20.340
that the scarce resource was
clever ideas, because I think

00:56:20.340 --> 00:56:22.510
of myself as a clever
idea kind of guy,

00:56:22.510 --> 00:56:24.310
and how flattering
it is to think

00:56:24.310 --> 00:56:27.770
that I'm what the world needs.

00:56:27.770 --> 00:56:31.530
But it turns out that just
probably within this room,

00:56:31.530 --> 00:56:36.360
there's enough clever
ideas to absorb

00:56:36.360 --> 00:56:39.070
the gross national product
of the United States

00:56:39.070 --> 00:56:42.925
for a number of years in R&amp;D.

00:56:42.925 --> 00:56:45.950
So the scarce resource
turns out to be

00:56:45.950 --> 00:56:52.930
the sort of intangible things
that we need within a society

00:56:52.930 --> 00:56:56.090
to mobilize capital
and to get these things

00:56:56.090 --> 00:56:57.900
actually moving forward.

00:56:57.900 --> 00:57:02.460
And that then turns into an
interesting conversation about,

00:57:02.460 --> 00:57:04.510
is it regulation?

00:57:04.510 --> 00:57:07.010
Is it the legal environment?

00:57:07.010 --> 00:57:11.030
Is it something to do
with how capitalists

00:57:11.030 --> 00:57:14.100
assess risk versus reward?

00:57:14.100 --> 00:57:15.820
I wish I could give
you a pat answer,

00:57:15.820 --> 00:57:17.800
but I bet Rudy's got one.

00:57:26.217 --> 00:57:27.300
RUDY RUCKER: Well, nature.

00:57:27.300 --> 00:57:28.966
You can always look
at what nature does.

00:57:28.966 --> 00:57:30.790
There's lots of
things competing.

00:57:30.790 --> 00:57:33.690
And I certainly agree that
we don't want monoculture

00:57:33.690 --> 00:57:35.160
with crops.

00:57:35.160 --> 00:57:39.134
It's just lots of
seething things.

00:57:39.134 --> 00:57:41.050
And people worry if you
do artificial biology,

00:57:41.050 --> 00:57:43.580
there will be some
creature you make

00:57:43.580 --> 00:57:45.190
that's going to be
like this super,

00:57:45.190 --> 00:57:47.820
super-slime that's
going to eat everything.

00:57:47.820 --> 00:57:51.000
But you need to keep in
mind that every living

00:57:51.000 --> 00:57:52.990
creature on earth
has been working

00:57:52.990 --> 00:57:56.650
to the very limits of its
capability for a billion years

00:57:56.650 --> 00:57:58.490
to try to dominate earth.

00:57:58.490 --> 00:58:01.720
So it's not that they are
not already trying to do it,

00:58:01.720 --> 00:58:04.110
but they keep each
other in check.

00:58:04.110 --> 00:58:06.190
It's not like we're going
to do something better

00:58:06.190 --> 00:58:09.020
just because we're scientists.

00:58:09.020 --> 00:58:10.560
We'll work on
something for a week

00:58:10.560 --> 00:58:12.420
and we're not going
to-- so I think

00:58:12.420 --> 00:58:15.300
that we can count on
the evolution of nature,

00:58:15.300 --> 00:58:19.216
but how to take over
politics, I don't know.

00:58:19.216 --> 00:58:21.340
I have to ask, as long as
I'm here, how many of you

00:58:21.340 --> 00:58:24.066
have read "The Circle,"
by David Eggers?

00:58:24.066 --> 00:58:26.480
Not too many people, yeah.

00:58:26.480 --> 00:58:29.810
It's sort of a "1984"
take on Google.

00:58:29.810 --> 00:58:32.300
It's a real page-turner.

00:58:32.300 --> 00:58:33.950
Makes you think twice.

00:58:33.950 --> 00:58:36.761
But enough said.

00:58:36.761 --> 00:58:39.252
[LAUGHTER]

00:58:39.252 --> 00:58:40.710
NEAL STEPHENSON:
One of the stories

00:58:40.710 --> 00:58:44.340
in Hieroglyph, by
Karl Schroeder,

00:58:44.340 --> 00:58:46.050
actually is about politics.

00:58:46.050 --> 00:58:50.710
So he actually went there
and addressed the topic

00:58:50.710 --> 00:58:54.350
of how might the way that
we prosecute politics

00:58:54.350 --> 00:59:00.390
change in the future, as
a way of actually enabling

00:59:00.390 --> 00:59:03.580
it to get things done that
we're not getting done now.

00:59:03.580 --> 00:59:04.180
ED FINN: Yeah.

00:59:04.180 --> 00:59:07.040
Another way of addressing what
you guys are talking about

00:59:07.040 --> 00:59:08.730
is that this is about
frame narratives.

00:59:08.730 --> 00:59:09.300
Right?

00:59:09.300 --> 00:59:11.500
You can spend all the
time in the world having

00:59:11.500 --> 00:59:15.330
the battle with the City
Council about how tall you

00:59:15.330 --> 00:59:16.110
can build stuff.

00:59:16.110 --> 00:59:18.690
But if you can come up with a
new story that's compelling,

00:59:18.690 --> 00:59:22.931
and if the people have a
different understanding of what

00:59:22.931 --> 00:59:24.680
a building is or what
we might do with it.

00:59:24.680 --> 00:59:25.888
What if a building is a city?

00:59:25.888 --> 00:59:29.220
What if a building is
an elevator into space?

00:59:29.220 --> 00:59:29.840
Right?

00:59:29.840 --> 00:59:31.150
ANNALEE NEWITZ: What if
it's a living organism?

00:59:31.150 --> 00:59:32.420
ED FINN: What if it's alive?

00:59:32.420 --> 00:59:32.920
Yeah.

00:59:32.920 --> 00:59:35.680
Well, what if it's a kite?

00:59:35.680 --> 00:59:38.720
Then that changes--
you know, learning

00:59:38.720 --> 00:59:40.720
to see the frame narrative
and figuring out ways

00:59:40.720 --> 00:59:42.760
you can change that
framing narrative,

00:59:42.760 --> 00:59:45.530
that's how you overcome
these other problems.

00:59:45.530 --> 00:59:50.280
It's a little bit like getting
a job in a very specific field.

00:59:50.280 --> 00:59:52.430
If you if you keep playing
the game by the rules,

00:59:52.430 --> 00:59:53.888
you're never going
to win the game.

00:59:53.888 --> 00:59:56.280
You have to learn how
to move the goalposts.

00:59:56.280 --> 00:59:59.230
ANNALEE NEWITZ: The good news
is politics are always changing.

00:59:59.230 --> 01:00:02.230
We think that there's this
sort of static narrative

01:00:02.230 --> 01:00:05.400
of the bad guys always win,
or the powerful people always

01:00:05.400 --> 01:00:06.670
crush the powerless people.

01:00:06.670 --> 01:00:08.600
But it's not always true.

01:00:08.600 --> 01:00:09.680
Things change a lot.

01:00:09.680 --> 01:00:12.500
Things have changed a lot
just in the past 10 years

01:00:12.500 --> 01:00:13.370
that we've seen.

01:00:13.370 --> 01:00:17.790
So we can intervene,
and things will change.

01:00:17.790 --> 01:00:20.030
And so maybe one
day, San Francisco

01:00:20.030 --> 01:00:22.100
will be a high-density
city with tall buildings.

01:00:22.100 --> 01:00:24.370
Wouldn't that be nice?

01:00:24.370 --> 01:00:27.620
KATHRYN CRAMER: And I
should say, on our way here

01:00:27.620 --> 01:00:31.900
we saw several large signs that
said "Neal for City Council."

01:00:31.900 --> 01:00:34.252
So maybe he'll change things.

01:00:34.252 --> 01:00:37.550
[LAUGHTER]

01:00:37.550 --> 01:00:41.490
AUDIENCE: As kind of a follow
up to the last question,

01:00:41.490 --> 01:00:44.960
the sort of canonical example
of the last really big, crazy

01:00:44.960 --> 01:00:47.330
thing we did was
the Apollo program.

01:00:47.330 --> 01:00:49.010
That kind of the
early '70s, which

01:00:49.010 --> 01:00:52.750
coincides with the beginning
of the great divergence

01:00:52.750 --> 01:00:57.300
and the beginning of the
fall of the public's trust

01:00:57.300 --> 01:00:58.410
in government.

01:00:58.410 --> 01:00:59.480
NEAL STEPHENSON: What's
the great divergence?

01:00:59.480 --> 01:01:00.480
AUDIENCE: Oh, pardon me.

01:01:00.480 --> 01:01:05.490
Between around-- from about
the time of the New Deal

01:01:05.490 --> 01:01:09.677
until around the 1970s, rising
tide really did lift all boats.

01:01:09.677 --> 01:01:11.260
Everyone's incomes
kind of got closer.

01:01:11.260 --> 01:01:12.940
Poor people were better off.

01:01:12.940 --> 01:01:18.084
After the 1970s, the gains
accrued to the very, very few.

01:01:18.084 --> 01:01:19.500
Including the
people in this room,

01:01:19.500 --> 01:01:22.790
but not very much below here.

01:01:22.790 --> 01:01:25.960
So do you see the
causality going--

01:01:25.960 --> 01:01:29.340
the being interested in
doing big things going hand

01:01:29.340 --> 01:01:31.940
in hand with her failures
a policy and loss of faith?

01:01:31.940 --> 01:01:33.960
Which direction you see
the causality going in?

01:01:35.845 --> 01:01:37.220
NEAL STEPHENSON:
Well that's kind

01:01:37.220 --> 01:01:39.040
of how this the
conversation started,

01:01:39.040 --> 01:01:44.345
as a sort of
conversation between me

01:01:44.345 --> 01:01:49.060
and Crow about which direction
the causality arrow pointed.

01:01:49.060 --> 01:01:55.250
So I'm not going to tell you
that I know what the answer is.

01:01:58.290 --> 01:02:00.880
This is one of those
"when you have a hammer,

01:02:00.880 --> 01:02:03.670
everything looks like a
nail" kind of conversations.

01:02:03.670 --> 01:02:07.370
So the thing that I've
been kind of officially

01:02:07.370 --> 01:02:11.150
certified by my civilization
as being qualified to do

01:02:11.150 --> 01:02:13.420
is to write science fiction.

01:02:13.420 --> 01:02:22.580
And so if I'm given an
opportunity to do that,

01:02:22.580 --> 01:02:25.990
and a university
president is telling me

01:02:25.990 --> 01:02:29.950
that maybe it'll
help, then I'm there.

01:02:29.950 --> 01:02:31.200
I'm a happy guy.

01:02:31.200 --> 01:02:35.810
I don't know whether--
so, part of what

01:02:35.810 --> 01:02:40.660
we're trying to figure out
is whether that actually

01:02:40.660 --> 01:02:44.897
does have any useful
causal effect.

01:02:44.897 --> 01:02:47.230
KATHRYN CRAMER: One thing
that was interesting about how

01:02:47.230 --> 01:02:50.040
the book turned out
is-- I mean, there's

01:02:50.040 --> 01:02:51.770
the themes we
asked for, and then

01:02:51.770 --> 01:02:54.820
there was what's
common in the stories

01:02:54.820 --> 01:02:56.300
we're actually publishing.

01:02:56.300 --> 01:03:00.410
And one of the surprise
themes of the book is empathy.

01:03:00.410 --> 01:03:02.840
There's a lot of stories that
are engaged with empathy,

01:03:02.840 --> 01:03:06.040
both just sort of thematically,
but also in some ways

01:03:06.040 --> 01:03:08.370
as a technological problem.

01:03:08.370 --> 01:03:11.530
ANNALEE NEWITZ: But also, I just
want to add in direct response

01:03:11.530 --> 01:03:16.000
to that question, what happens
when you have extreme class

01:03:16.000 --> 01:03:22.489
divisions in a culture and the
middle class is disappearing?

01:03:22.489 --> 01:03:24.780
Which has already happened
in other parts of the world.

01:03:24.780 --> 01:03:27.500
So we're just-- the US
is kind of catching up.

01:03:30.120 --> 01:03:32.990
That means that fewer and
fewer people are allowed

01:03:32.990 --> 01:03:36.470
to be authorized, like Neal,
to have ideas and participate

01:03:36.470 --> 01:03:42.090
in making decisions about
what a nation will do next,

01:03:42.090 --> 01:03:44.730
or what a university
will fund next,

01:03:44.730 --> 01:03:47.060
or what a pharmaceutical
company will fund next.

01:03:47.060 --> 01:03:49.350
And the more homogeneous
that group gets,

01:03:49.350 --> 01:03:51.620
and the more we
exclude people from it,

01:03:51.620 --> 01:03:53.260
the fewer and
fewer ideas we get.

01:03:53.260 --> 01:03:55.010
Because of course,
ideas-- we were just

01:03:55.010 --> 01:03:56.620
talking about
diversity in nature,

01:03:56.620 --> 01:04:01.110
and I think the best ideas come
from diversity in humans too.

01:04:01.110 --> 01:04:02.950
It's just good sense.

01:04:02.950 --> 01:04:05.650
And so I think if
there is-- I also

01:04:05.650 --> 01:04:07.494
think there's no simple
causal explanation.

01:04:07.494 --> 01:04:08.660
I think that would be silly.

01:04:08.660 --> 01:04:10.080
I wish there were.

01:04:10.080 --> 01:04:12.140
But I do think that
there's a correlation

01:04:12.140 --> 01:04:14.780
between a difficulty
in coming up

01:04:14.780 --> 01:04:19.250
with big ideas and a culture
that's strongly class-divided.

01:04:19.250 --> 01:04:22.780
RUDY RUCKER: I have one more
thing to say about that.

01:04:22.780 --> 01:04:28.240
One of the other paradigms,
besides getting the public

01:04:28.240 --> 01:04:32.390
to chip in a very large amount
of money to make a giant tower,

01:04:32.390 --> 01:04:38.780
or to map the genome, or
to build a highway network,

01:04:38.780 --> 01:04:42.710
is more of the indie,
do-it-yourself ethic.

01:04:42.710 --> 01:04:46.770
It's the old punk thing
of turning your back

01:04:46.770 --> 01:04:48.580
on the authorities
and doing it yourself.

01:04:48.580 --> 01:04:50.210
And that was sort
of-- that was one

01:04:50.210 --> 01:04:53.960
of the elements of
cyberpunk, is the concept

01:04:53.960 --> 01:04:58.390
that you can have these
off-the-grid sorts of people.

01:04:58.390 --> 01:05:01.610
Like Blank Reg in
"Max Headroom."

01:05:01.610 --> 01:05:05.474
And they're doing it and make
it happen in their own ways.

01:05:05.474 --> 01:05:06.890
That's something
Cory Doctorow has

01:05:06.890 --> 01:05:12.620
been writing a lot in his recent
books, like "Pirate Cinema."

01:05:12.620 --> 01:05:17.240
And I think there's
some hope with that.

01:05:17.240 --> 01:05:24.970
This said, to make a really
massive, key technical

01:05:24.970 --> 01:05:27.580
scientific breakthrough,
it's not clear

01:05:27.580 --> 01:05:32.461
that Santa Cruz stoners can
do that in their kitchen.

01:05:32.461 --> 01:05:36.800
[LAUGHTER] Maybe they can.

01:05:36.800 --> 01:05:39.670
Let them try.

01:05:39.670 --> 01:05:41.620
NEAL STEPHENSON:
So I'll just try

01:05:41.620 --> 01:05:46.900
to quickly say there's sort of
three general ways-- paradigms

01:05:46.900 --> 01:05:50.010
for organizing a bunch of
geeks-- that I think of.

01:05:50.010 --> 01:05:56.200
And one is the hacker,
edge-dwelling kind of people,

01:05:56.200 --> 01:05:58.340
exemplified maybe by Linux.

01:05:58.340 --> 01:06:01.480
One is the kind of Stalinist
government-funded program.

01:06:01.480 --> 01:06:07.430
And one is the big
company doing it.

01:06:07.430 --> 01:06:08.980
One of the interesting
things, to me,

01:06:08.980 --> 01:06:11.870
about the results of the
Hieroglyph experiment

01:06:11.870 --> 01:06:14.527
was that there wasn't a
lot of the third thing.

01:06:14.527 --> 01:06:16.360
There wasn't even a lot
of the second thing.

01:06:16.360 --> 01:06:20.420
So there was a still a pretty
strong reliance on the outsider

01:06:20.420 --> 01:06:23.380
hacker-type self-organizing
to make stuff.

01:06:23.380 --> 01:06:25.750
I thought it was
interesting that it seemed

01:06:25.750 --> 01:06:27.930
to reflect a kind
of lack of vision,

01:06:27.930 --> 01:06:31.400
or lack of faith in the
ability of big institutions--

01:06:31.400 --> 01:06:35.970
be they governments or
companies-- to actually

01:06:35.970 --> 01:06:38.700
mobilize engineers
and get things done.

01:06:38.700 --> 01:06:41.830
Which I think is funny,
because that's actually

01:06:41.830 --> 01:06:46.210
where engineers are
employed and do things.

01:06:46.210 --> 01:06:48.300
But seen from the
outside, there seems

01:06:48.300 --> 01:06:50.890
to be a lack of
faith or optimism

01:06:50.890 --> 01:06:53.694
about the ability of big
companies to do stuff.

01:06:53.694 --> 01:06:55.860
ANNALEE NEWITZ: I have lots
of municipal governments

01:06:55.860 --> 01:06:57.073
in my story.

01:06:57.073 --> 01:06:58.530
NEAL STEPHENSON: There you go.

01:06:58.530 --> 01:07:02.550
ANNALEE NEWITZ: I have faith
in the municipal government.

01:07:02.550 --> 01:07:03.200
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:07:03.200 --> 01:07:06.900
Actually, I want to kind of--
it's rather a specific question

01:07:06.900 --> 01:07:08.380
about the tall tower idea.

01:07:08.380 --> 01:07:11.260
I mean, in software
we kind of are

01:07:11.260 --> 01:07:16.050
taught to write code that
kind of fails graciously.

01:07:16.050 --> 01:07:19.420
So the question would be:
How would the tall tower

01:07:19.420 --> 01:07:21.255
fall graciously?

01:07:21.255 --> 01:07:22.880
NEAL STEPHENSON:
Keith's all over that!

01:07:22.880 --> 01:07:24.088
KEITH HJELMSTAD: It wouldn't.

01:07:24.088 --> 01:07:25.677
There would be a
massive catastrophe.

01:07:25.677 --> 01:07:28.260
There's no such thing as a large
structure falling gracefully.

01:07:28.260 --> 01:07:29.385
AUDIENCE: That's an excuse.

01:07:29.385 --> 01:07:30.920
You know that, right?

01:07:30.920 --> 01:07:31.780
It will fall.

01:07:31.780 --> 01:07:33.406
But how do you make
it fall graciously?

01:07:33.406 --> 01:07:34.696
KEITH HJELMSTAD: It won't fall.

01:07:34.696 --> 01:07:35.270
Ever.

01:07:35.270 --> 01:07:40.860
[LAUGHTER] After the Earth
has banished all species,

01:07:40.860 --> 01:07:43.792
there it will be standing.

01:07:43.792 --> 01:07:45.250
NEAL STEPHENSON:
In the story, just

01:07:45.250 --> 01:07:51.110
to avoid worrying about it, I
stipulate that downwind of it

01:07:51.110 --> 01:07:53.090
there's a big thing
that's literally

01:07:53.090 --> 01:07:56.820
called "the swath," which-- the
billionaire who makes it just

01:07:56.820 --> 01:07:58.970
buys all of that land.

01:07:58.970 --> 01:08:00.710
And so the way he
shuts people up

01:08:00.710 --> 01:08:03.780
when they're worrying that the
tower's going to fall over,

01:08:03.780 --> 01:08:06.170
is that he says, "If
it starts to fall,

01:08:06.170 --> 01:08:08.920
we'll just dynamite all
of the legs on that side,

01:08:08.920 --> 01:08:11.830
and the entire tower will
just fall like a tree

01:08:11.830 --> 01:08:13.700
down the swath, and
we'll keep the swath

01:08:13.700 --> 01:08:19.550
empty in the meantime,
to minimize the fallout."

01:08:19.550 --> 01:08:20.240
But that's me.

01:08:20.240 --> 01:08:24.305
That's not a legitimate
engineering contribution.

01:08:27.029 --> 01:08:28.850
AUDIENCE: One
thing I've enjoyed,

01:08:28.850 --> 01:08:31.149
slash, struggled with
in Neal's writing

01:08:31.149 --> 01:08:37.130
a lot is that it's really hard
to remember what he's making up

01:08:37.130 --> 01:08:38.800
and what is factual.

01:08:38.800 --> 01:08:40.910
And that delight
and frustrates me.

01:08:40.910 --> 01:08:44.270
And I'm wondering,
how in this anthology

01:08:44.270 --> 01:08:47.540
did you-- did the writers
manage to walk that line so

01:08:47.540 --> 01:08:50.729
closely, where you have
to keep track-- wait!

01:08:50.729 --> 01:08:54.193
Did I read about that in a
novel or a science journal?

01:08:54.193 --> 01:08:55.609
NEAL STEPHENSON:
Well, that sounds

01:08:55.609 --> 01:08:58.970
like what Rudy's been
working on with his notes,

01:08:58.970 --> 01:09:04.166
his ongoing note-keeping system.

01:09:04.166 --> 01:09:05.760
I'm terrible at that.

01:09:08.370 --> 01:09:12.170
RUDY RUCKER: I do like to
have a coherent theory.

01:09:12.170 --> 01:09:13.950
That's one sort
of-- you might say

01:09:13.950 --> 01:09:17.090
that's one difference between
science fiction and fantasy,

01:09:17.090 --> 01:09:20.720
is fantasy you're not required
to have a coherent underlying

01:09:20.720 --> 01:09:23.019
theory of why the
events happened.

01:09:23.019 --> 01:09:24.210
They're just there.

01:09:24.210 --> 01:09:26.830
It's sort of like X-Files.

01:09:26.830 --> 01:09:28.630
It's strange!

01:09:28.630 --> 01:09:29.810
What if?!

01:09:29.810 --> 01:09:33.330
But if you're writing something
that's more like hard science

01:09:33.330 --> 01:09:37.870
fiction, then you make
up-- like, somebody

01:09:37.870 --> 01:09:40.300
use the word, "rubber
science," or-- that's

01:09:40.300 --> 01:09:44.200
a bit denigrating--
nonstandard science.

01:09:44.200 --> 01:09:47.540
You add on some
extra principles.

01:09:47.540 --> 01:09:50.979
I got my Ph.D. in mathematical
logics, and as I said,

01:09:50.979 --> 01:09:55.050
I taught programming
for 20 years.

01:09:55.050 --> 01:09:57.250
So I like the idea of
having a logical system

01:09:57.250 --> 01:09:59.130
and either deducing
things or-- it's

01:09:59.130 --> 01:10:01.520
like if you have a program,
you look at the outputs.

01:10:01.520 --> 01:10:04.960
So I like whatever
I'm doing in the story

01:10:04.960 --> 01:10:07.330
to have an underlying theory.

01:10:07.330 --> 01:10:09.580
And I don't actually start
with a theory and work out.

01:10:09.580 --> 01:10:11.880
I start with the
effects I want to see.

01:10:11.880 --> 01:10:15.180
I want to see something
really cool, like a tower.

01:10:15.180 --> 01:10:17.440
And then I want to
see people flying.

01:10:17.440 --> 01:10:20.125
And I want people to have
telepathy with each other.

01:10:20.125 --> 01:10:23.250
Then I say, OK, so how are
we going to make this happen?

01:10:23.250 --> 01:10:27.100
And that's-- the technical term
for what you're looking for is

01:10:27.100 --> 01:10:30.700
what's called a
"bogosity generator."

01:10:30.700 --> 01:10:33.810
So you get your bogosity
generator, but you make logic.

01:10:33.810 --> 01:10:34.880
You build it solid.

01:10:34.880 --> 01:10:38.450
You don't just throw
together some woo-woo crap.

01:10:38.450 --> 01:10:41.950
You've got something--
you make up whatever.

01:10:41.950 --> 01:10:44.583
Dark energy is great. you know?

01:10:44.583 --> 01:10:48.580
[LAUGHTER] 90% of the
universe is dark energy.

01:10:48.580 --> 01:10:50.860
That sort of tells you
something, doesn't it?

01:10:50.860 --> 01:10:53.800
90% of the universe is bullshit!

01:10:53.800 --> 01:10:56.421
So it's all about
keeping a straight face

01:10:56.421 --> 01:10:57.670
when you're writing the story.

01:10:57.670 --> 01:11:00.730
You just pile it on and
you keep a straight face.

01:11:00.730 --> 01:11:04.760
ED FINN: One of the fun things
about-- That was a good answer!

01:11:04.760 --> 01:11:06.720
But one of the fun
things about this project

01:11:06.720 --> 01:11:10.760
is that it's not entirely clear
whether some of these stories

01:11:10.760 --> 01:11:13.640
are really science
fiction at all anymore.

01:11:13.640 --> 01:11:18.430
There's a story called, "Johnny
Appledrone vs. the FAA,"

01:11:18.430 --> 01:11:21.230
which is about the
near future of drones.

01:11:21.230 --> 01:11:25.020
And it's not-- there's
really nothing,

01:11:25.020 --> 01:11:28.190
I think, in the story that's
technically impossible now.

01:11:28.190 --> 01:11:30.760
And obviously,
certain people seem

01:11:30.760 --> 01:11:32.150
to be quite
interested in drones.

01:11:35.860 --> 01:11:38.010
And Cory Doctorow's
story for the anthology

01:11:38.010 --> 01:11:40.610
also involves an
area of research

01:11:40.610 --> 01:11:43.740
that NASA and the European Space
Agency has funded for, I think,

01:11:43.740 --> 01:11:48.480
for several years on what
I've recently learned

01:11:48.480 --> 01:11:50.505
is called "in situ
resource utilization."

01:11:50.505 --> 01:11:52.130
What if, instead of
carrying everything

01:11:52.130 --> 01:11:55.140
you need to the moon, you
can use all the resources

01:11:55.140 --> 01:11:56.420
on the moon or on Mars?

01:11:56.420 --> 01:11:59.390
Other destinations?

01:11:59.390 --> 01:12:02.500
To 3D print, or otherwise
fabricate the materials

01:12:02.500 --> 01:12:03.160
that you need.

01:12:05.850 --> 01:12:08.230
The most implausible
stuff in Cory's story

01:12:08.230 --> 01:12:10.140
is not that, I think.

01:12:10.140 --> 01:12:17.110
It's about other social features
of the near future society

01:12:17.110 --> 01:12:20.200
and economic predictions
about how expensive

01:12:20.200 --> 01:12:23.191
it will be to launch
stuff into space.

01:12:23.191 --> 01:12:25.190
KATHRYN CRAMER: One thing
about the organization

01:12:25.190 --> 01:12:27.610
of Hieroglyph as
a book, is there's

01:12:27.610 --> 01:12:29.440
a lot more "showing
your work" in it.

01:12:29.440 --> 01:12:31.980
We have the authors
write stuff about where

01:12:31.980 --> 01:12:35.170
they got their ideas and how
they work them out, and so on.

01:12:35.170 --> 01:12:38.800
So in a usual science
fiction anthology,

01:12:38.800 --> 01:12:42.550
we try to hide all that stuff
so that you just believe as much

01:12:42.550 --> 01:12:43.390
of it as possible.

01:12:43.390 --> 01:12:45.050
But because of the
nature of this book,

01:12:45.050 --> 01:12:48.470
we exposed a lot more than
we otherwise would have.

01:12:48.470 --> 01:12:51.705
NEAL STEPHENSON: That's
actually sort of a Cramer family

01:12:51.705 --> 01:12:52.205
tradition.

01:12:52.205 --> 01:12:53.038
KATHRYN CRAMER: Yes!

01:12:53.038 --> 01:12:58.200
NEAL STEPHENSON: In
"Twistor," at the end,

01:12:58.200 --> 01:13:02.170
he adds a little
technical appendix

01:13:02.170 --> 01:13:05.135
explaining the bogosity part.

01:13:05.135 --> 01:13:09.740
He says, well, OK, it's
all true up to page 93,

01:13:09.740 --> 01:13:12.500
and then he gives a
complete sort of physics

01:13:12.500 --> 01:13:17.290
explanation of where he departed
from something you could

01:13:17.290 --> 01:13:19.439
put into a
peer-reviewed journal.

01:13:19.439 --> 01:13:20.730
MODERATOR: Last quick question.

01:13:20.730 --> 01:13:21.490
NEAL STEPHENSON: OK.

01:13:21.490 --> 01:13:23.739
AUDIENCE: So I've been told
I need to keep this quick.

01:13:23.739 --> 01:13:28.270
The thing most like near sci-fi
that I've heard of recently

01:13:28.270 --> 01:13:29.020
is Bitcoin.

01:13:29.020 --> 01:13:30.360
It's kind of crazy.

01:13:30.360 --> 01:13:32.680
And I was just hoping
that you guys might

01:13:32.680 --> 01:13:37.120
give an idea of-- is this a
step on the way towards utopia

01:13:37.120 --> 01:13:37.990
or dystopia?

01:13:37.990 --> 01:13:39.627
Like, I can't--

01:13:39.627 --> 01:13:40.960
RUDY RUCKER: Neal has a Bitcoin.

01:13:40.960 --> 01:13:42.536
He showed it to me at lunch.

01:13:42.536 --> 01:13:44.120
[LAUGHTER]

01:13:44.120 --> 01:13:46.440
NEAL STEPHENSON: Someone
gave me a Bitcoin.

01:13:46.440 --> 01:13:48.770
ED FINN: Let me channel
Karl Schroeder for a second,

01:13:48.770 --> 01:13:51.009
since his story-- he
actually got in touch with us

01:13:51.009 --> 01:13:52.550
in the middle of
production and said,

01:13:52.550 --> 01:13:55.680
"I have to revise my story to
include the block chain, which

01:13:55.680 --> 01:13:58.150
is the central
technology of Bitcoin.

01:13:58.150 --> 01:14:01.410
It's something I've become
quite interested in recently."

01:14:01.410 --> 01:14:04.870
But basically, Karl
is taking the lead

01:14:04.870 --> 01:14:07.250
of people who are saying
Bitcoin-- don't think

01:14:07.250 --> 01:14:10.240
about Bitcoin as a
system for currency.

01:14:10.240 --> 01:14:13.810
Think about it as a system for
democracy and authenticating

01:14:13.810 --> 01:14:16.450
stuff through a
peer-to-peer network.

01:14:16.450 --> 01:14:19.900
And so he-- Neal
already mentioned

01:14:19.900 --> 01:14:22.730
that his narrative is about the
political, potential political

01:14:22.730 --> 01:14:23.650
impact of technology.

01:14:23.650 --> 01:14:27.670
Could you solve
consensus-based decision-making

01:14:27.670 --> 01:14:30.900
if you just had better
Wi-Fi and better interface

01:14:30.900 --> 01:14:33.270
tools for getting people to
understand issues and make

01:14:33.270 --> 01:14:34.580
decisions about them?

01:14:34.580 --> 01:14:37.400
And so he really wanted to make
sure the block chain was part

01:14:37.400 --> 01:14:40.110
of that, as another
tool that you

01:14:40.110 --> 01:14:44.560
would use to authenticate a
consensus-based decision model.

01:14:44.560 --> 01:14:50.490
So I'm not so sure, but
Karl thinks it's utopian.

01:14:50.490 --> 01:14:51.810
Thank you so much.

01:14:51.810 --> 01:14:53.010
This was great.

01:14:53.010 --> 01:14:56.060
[APPLAUSE]

